IBADAN – No fewer than 25 unemployed youths who are graduates of various institutions of learn­ing across the country have benefitted from the National Directorate of Employment (NDE) solar power installation and maintenance training in Ogun State. NDE, in partnership with Abuja Graduate School re­cently completed a five-day in­tensive training for 25 youths on solar power installation and maintenance in Ogun State. Speaking during the com­mencement of the training in Abeokuta the Ogun State capi­tal, the NDE Director-General, Mallam Abubakar Nuhu Fikpo maintained that the training was packaged to eliminate the growing of darkness within communities due to irregular­ities in public electric power supply and also to empower unemployed youths. Buhari Inaugurates NNPC Board, Outlines Guidelines For… NIA DG Never Failed Promotion Examination – ONSA Mallam Nuhu, who was represented at the event by the Ogun State NDE Coordinator, Mr. Alao Babatunde Ismail stressed that the training was intended to impact the train­ees with the requisite skills to provide renewable energy to mitigate the shortfall in electric power supply. He further reiterated that the training will be anchored by experienced resource per­sons in order to ensure the proficiency of the trainees at the end of the training period. He, therefore, implored the participants to strive to partic­ipate effectively so that at the end of the training, the objec­tives of the training will be op­timally achieved, stressing that the solar installation and main­tenance training is an integral part of President Muhamma­du Buhari’s agenda to take 100 million people out of poverty by the year 2030, at the rate of 10 million people every year.